00:58:37,260 --> 00:58:38,850
Him? What about me?

768
00:58:39,060 --> 00:58:41,460
Crazy old fool damn near cut my throat!

769
00:58:41,670 --> 00:58:43,570
You've had worse from shaving.

770
00:58:43,770 --> 00:58:45,860
What did you do to set him off?

771
00:58:46,070 --> 00:58:48,300
Nothing.
I come in here to say farewell.

772
00:58:48,910 --> 00:58:51,570
Ain't you heard?
His parole's come through.

773
00:58:53,910 --> 00:58:56,710
I just don't understand
what happened in there.

774
00:58:56,910 --> 00:58:59,710
Old man's crazy as a rat
in a tin shithouse.

775
00:58:59,920 --> 00:59:01,820
That's enough out of you.

776
00:59:02,020 --> 00:59:04,750
- Heard he had you shitting your pants.
- Fuck you.

777
00:59:05,020 --> 00:59:06,220
IKnock it off.

778
00:59:07,190 --> 00:59:08,620
Brooks ain't no bug.

779
00:59:12,460 --> 00:59:14,230
He's just institutionalized.

780
00:59:15,600 --> 00:59:17,530
"Institutionalized," my ass.

781
00:59:17,730 --> 00:59:21,730
The man's been in here 50 years,
Heywood, 50 years!

782
00:59:21,940 --> 00:59:23,670
This is all he knows.

783
00:59:23,870 --> 00:59:26,170
In here, he's an important man...

784
00:59:26,380 --> 00:59:27,470
...an educated man.

785
00:59:28,280 --> 00:59:30,210
Outside, he's nothing.

786
00:59:31,080 --> 00:59:34,570
Just a used-up con
with arthritis in both hands.

787
00:59:34,790 --> 00:59:37,780
Probably couldn't get a library card
if he tried.

788
00:59:38,060 --> 00:59:39,780
You know what I'm trying to say?

789
00:59:40,060 --> 00:59:42,960
I do believe
you're talking out of your ass.

790
00:59:44,230 --> 00:59:46,460
You believe whatever you want.

791
00:59:47,060 --> 00:59:49,460
But I tell you these walls are funny.

792
00:59:51,070 --> 00:59:52,730
First you hate them.

793
00:59:54,570 --> 00:59:56,470
Then you get used to them.

794
00:59:58,410 --> 01:00:00,400
Enough time passes...

795
01:00:01,080 --> 01:00:03,070
...you get so you depend on them.

796
01:00:04,080 --> 01:00:06,280
That's "institutionalized."

797
01:00:06,480 --> 01:00:07,780
Shit.

798
01:00:07,980 --> 01:00:10,750
- I could never get like that.
- Oh, yeah?

799
01:00:11,620 --> 01:00:14,110
Wait till you've been here
as long as Brooks.

800
01:00:14,360 --> 01:00:15,920
Goddamn right.

801
01:00:18,500 --> 01:00:20,430
They send you here for life...

802
01:00:21,100 --> 01:00:23,430
...that's exactly what they take.

803
01:00:25,170 --> 01:00:27,160
Part that counts, anyway.

804
01:00:34,780 --> 01:00:37,710
I can't take care of you no more, Jake.

805
01:00:38,880 --> 01:00:40,540
You go on now.

806
01:00:41,790 --> 01:00:43,280
You're free.

807
01:00:44,550 --> 01:00:46,110
You're free.

808
01:01:05,140 --> 01:01:06,800
Good luck, Brooksie.

809
01:01:44,780 --> 01:01:46,270
Dear fellas:

810
01:01:46,550 --> 01:01:50,750
I can't believe how fast things move
on the outside.

811
01:01:52,060 --> 01:01:54,720
Watch it, old-timer!
Want to get killed?

812
01:01:55,960 --> 01:01:59,450
I saw an automobile once
when I was a kid...

813
01:02:00,100 --> 01:02:02,530
... but now they're everywhere.

814
01:02:06,200 --> 01:02:10,500
The world went and got itself
in a big damn hurry.

815
01:02:26,320 --> 01:02:30,090
The parole board
got me into this halfway house...

816
01:02:30,390 --> 01:02:32,050
... called "The Brewster"...

817
01:02:32,260 --> 01:02:33,420
... and a job...

818
01:02:33,630 --> 01:02:36,600
... bagging groceries at the Food-Way.

819
01:02:38,130 --> 01:02:40,570
It's hard work and I try to keep up...

820
01:02:40,770 --> 01:02:43,140
... but my hands hurt most of the time.

821
01:02:43,440 --> 01:02:45,410
Make sure your man double-bags.

822
01:02:45,610 --> 01:02:47,630
Last time, the bottom near came out.

823
01:02:48,310 --> 01:02:51,250
Make sure you double-bag
like the lady says. Understand?

824
01:02:51,450 --> 01:02:52,810
Yes, sir. Surely will.

825
01:02:53,020 --> 01:02:56,540
I don't think the store manager
likes me very much.

826
01:02:59,560 --> 01:03:03,860
Sometimes after work,
I go to the park and feed the birds.

827
01:03:04,290 --> 01:03:05,780
I keep thinking...

828
01:03:06,030 --> 01:03:09,360
... Jake might just show up
and say hello.

829
01:03:09,970 --> 01:03:11,960
But he never does.

830
01:03:13,170 --> 01:03:18,040
I hope, wherever he is, he's doing okay
and making new friends.

831
01:03:21,650 --> 01:03:24,380
I have trouble sleeping at night.

832
01:03:24,680 --> 01:03:27,950
I have bad dreams like I'm falling.

833
01:03:28,220 --> 01:03:30,450
I wake up scared.

834
01:03:30,650 --> 01:03:34,890
Sometimes it takes me a while
to remember where I am.

835
01:03:36,390 --> 01:03:41,300
Maybe I should get a gun and rob
the Food-Way so they'd send me home.

836
01:03:41,600 --> 01:03:45,930
I could shoot the manager while
I was at it. Sort of like a bonus.

837
01:03:47,600 --> 01:03:51,600
I guess I'm too old
for that sort of nonsense anymore.

838
01:03:51,840 --> 01:03:53,570
I don't like it here.

839
01:03:53,780 --> 01:03:57,770
I'm tired of being afraid all the time.
I've decided...

840
01:03:58,620 --> 01:04:00,280
... not to stay.

841
01:04:11,190 --> 01:04:13,750
I doubt they'll kick up any fuss...

842
01:04:13,960 --> 01:04:17,460
... not for an old crook like me.

843
01:05:19,930 --> 01:05:24,200
"I doubt they'll kick up any fuss,
not for an old crook like me.

844
01:05:25,240 --> 01:05:29,070
P.S. Tell Heywood I'm sorry
I put a knife to his throat.

845
01:05:29,270 --> 01:05:31,600
No hard feelings. Brooks."

846
01:05:42,090 --> 01:05:44,050
He should have died in here.

847
01:05:49,590 --> 01:05:50,990
What the fuck have you done?

848
01:05:51,190 --> 01:05:53,860
It's a goddamn mess,
I'll tell you that.

849
01:05:59,400 --> 01:06:03,130
- What's all this?
- You tell me. They're addressed to you.

850
01:06:04,410 --> 01:06:05,740
Take it.

851
01:06:14,280 --> 01:06:15,770
"Dear Mr. Dufresne:

852
01:06:16,920 --> 01:06:18,890
In response to your inquiries...

853
01:06:19,090 --> 01:06:23,350
...the state has allocated the enclosed
funds for your library project."

854
01:06:24,130 --> 01:06:25,960
This is $ 200.

855
01:06:26,160 --> 01:06:30,160
"In addition, the library district
has generously responded...

856
01:06:30,370 --> 01:06:32,930
...with a donation of used books
and sundries.

857
01:06:33,140 --> 01:06:37,270
We trust this will fill your needs.
We now consider the matter closed.

858
01:06:37,470 --> 01:06:39,270
Please stop sending us letters."

859
01:06:39,510 --> 01:06:42,170
Clear all this out
before the warden gets back.

860
01:06:42,410 --> 01:06:43,570
Yes, sir.

861
01:06:47,850 --> 01:06:49,010
Good for you, Andy.

862
01:06:51,990 --> 01:06:53,110
Wow!

863
01:06:54,320 --> 01:06:56,260
It only took six years.

864
01:06:57,830 --> 01:07:00,560
From now on, I'll write two
letters a week instead of one.

865
01:07:00,760 --> 01:07:04,100
I believe you're crazy enough.
Get this stuff out...

866
01:07:04,370 --> 01:07:05,200
...like he said.

867
01:07:05,400 --> 01:07:06,800
I've got to pinch a loaf.

868
01:07:07,000 --> 01:07:08,470
When I come back...

869
01:07:08,670 --> 01:07:10,430
...this is all gone, all right?

870
01:07:59,190 --> 01:08:00,590
Do you hear that?

871
01:09:09,330 --> 01:09:10,490
Dufresne!

872
01:09:13,030 --> 01:09:14,550
Andy, let me out!

873
01:09:21,440 --> 01:09:26,370
I have no idea to this day what those
two Italian ladies were singing about.

874
01:09:26,680 --> 01:09:28,910
Truth is, I don't want to know.

875
01:09:29,110 --> 01:09:31,600
Some things are best left unsaid.

876
01:09:35,180 --> 01:09:37,910
I like to think it was something
so beautiful...

877
01:09:38,120 --> 01:09:40,250
... it can't be expressed in words...

878
01:09:40,460 --> 01:09:43,360
... and makes your heart ache
because of it.

879
01:09:45,030 --> 01:09:47,520
I tell you, those voices soared...

880
01:09:47,800 --> 01:09:52,100
... higher and farther than anybody
in a gray place dares to dream.

881
01:09:52,300 --> 01:09:55,670
It was like a beautiful bird
flapped into our drab cage...

882
01:09:55,870 --> 01:09:58,640
... and made those walls dissolve away.

883
01:09:59,080 --> 01:10:01,270
And for the briefest of moments...

884
01:10:01,480 --> 01:10:04,470
... every last man at Shawshank
felt free.

885
01:10:07,050 --> 01:10:09,710
It pissed the warden off
something awful.

886
01:10:11,020 --> 01:10:12,010
Open the door.

887
01:10:14,920 --> 01:10:16,690
Open it up!

888
01:10:17,990 --> 01:10:20,720
Dufresne, open this door!

889
01:10:22,070 --> 01:10:23,260
Turn that off!

890
01:10:30,340 --> 01:10:32,770
I am warning you. Turn that off!

891
01:10:50,530 --> 01:10:52,050
You're mine now.

892
01:10:59,500 --> 01:11:02,730
Andy got two weeks in the hole
for that little stunt.

893
01:11:02,940 --> 01:11:04,530
On your feet.

894
01:11:05,710 --> 01:11:08,110
- Hey, look who's here.
- Maestro!

895
01:11:09,880 --> 01:11:13,540
You couldn't play something good, huh?
Like Hank Williams?

896
01:11:13,880 --> 01:11:16,680
They broke the door down
before I could take requests.

897
01:11:16,890 --> 01:11:20,010
- Was it worth two weeks?
- Easiest time I ever did.

898
01:11:20,220 --> 01:11:24,420
- No such thing as easy time in the hole.
- A week in the hole is like a year.

899
01:11:24,630 --> 01:11:27,930
- Damn straight.
- I had Mr. Mozart to keep me company.

900
01:11:28,130 --> 01:11:31,100
So they let you tote
that record player down there, huh?

901
01:11:33,540 --> 01:11:34,900
It was in here.

902
01:11:35,740 --> 01:11:36,970
In here.

903
01:11:38,110 --> 01:11:40,200
That's the beauty of music. They...

904
01:11:40,410 --> 01:11:42,740
...can't get that from you.

905
01:11:46,280 --> 01:11:48,650
Haven't you ever felt
that way about music?

906
01:11:50,450 --> 01:11:53,580
Well, I played a mean harmonica
as a younger man.

907
01:11:54,620 --> 01:11:56,320
Lost interest in it, though.

908
01:11:56,530 --> 01:11:58,120
Didn't make much sense in here.

909
01:11:58,460 --> 01:12:00,450
Here's where it makes the most sense.

910
01:12:01,000 --> 01:12:03,060
You need it so you don't forget.

911
01:12:03,630 --> 01:12:04,830
Forget?

912
01:12:05,200 --> 01:12:08,300
Forget that there are...

913
01:12:08,500 --> 01:12:09,940
...places...

914
01:12:10,440 --> 01:12:14,270
...in the world
that aren't made out of stone.

915
01:12:15,280 --> 01:12:16,770
There's something...

916
01:12:17,110 --> 01:12:18,510
...inside...

917
01:12:18,780 --> 01:12:20,750
...that they can't get to...

918
01:12:20,950 --> 01:12:22,320
...that they can't touch.

919
01:12:22,850 --> 01:12:24,290
That's yours.

920
01:12:25,820 --> 01:12:27,410
What are you talking about?

921
01:12:28,460 --> 01:12:29,690
Hope.

922
01:12:30,760 --> 01:12:32,090
Hope.

923
01:12:34,030 --> 01:12:36,020
Let me tell you something, my friend.

924
01:12:36,830 --> 01:12:39,130
Hope is a dangerous thing.

925
01:12:40,300 --> 01:12:42,640
Hope can drive a man insane.

926
01:12:43,370 --> 01:12:45,500
It's got no use on the inside.

927
01:12:45,710 --> 01:12:47,900
You'd better get used to that idea.

928
01:12:50,410 --> 01:12:51,900
Like Brooks did?

929
01:13:17,270 --> 01:13:18,260
Sit down.

930
01:13:23,610 --> 01:13:26,910
Says here that you've served
30 years of a life sentence.

931
01:13:28,080 --> 01:13:30,140
You feel you've been rehabilitated?

932
01:13:30,350 --> 01:13:31,580
Oh, yes, sir.

933
01:13:32,860 --> 01:13:34,190
Without a doubt.

934
01:13:35,360 --> 01:13:37,760
I can honestly say I'm a changed man.

935
01:13:39,760 --> 01:13:41,700
No danger to society here.

936
01:13:42,230 --> 01:13:43,760
God's honest truth.

937
01:13:46,340 --> 01:13:48,430
Absolutely rehabilitated.

938
01:13:58,410 --> 01:13:59,740
Thirty years.

939
01:14:01,720 --> 01:14:03,620
Jesus, when you say it like that...

940
01:14:04,480 --> 01:14:06,280
You wonder where it went.

941
01:14:08,720 --> 01:14:10,880
I wonder where 10 years went.

942
01:14:15,860 --> 01:14:16,890
Here.

943
01:14:17,330 --> 01:14:20,060
A little parole rejection present.

944
01:14:21,330 --> 01:14:23,030
Go ahead and open it.

945
01:14:24,140 --> 01:14:26,160
Went through one of your competitors.

946
01:14:26,370 --> 01:14:29,500
I hope you don't mind.
I wanted it to be a surprise.

947
01:14:39,550 --> 01:14:41,040
It's very pretty.

948
01:14:42,760 --> 01:14:43,950
Thank you.

949
01:14:46,530 --> 01:14:47,990
You going to play it?

950
01:14:52,570 --> 01:14:53,830
No.

951
01:14:57,440 --> 01:14:58,840
Not right now.

952
01:15:16,520 --> 01:15:17,620
Roll in!

953
01:15:53,830 --> 01:15:55,060
Lights out!

954
01:16:29,660 --> 01:16:31,790
Andy was as good as his word.

955
01:16:32,170 --> 01:16:34,930
He wrote two letters a week
instead of one.

956
01:16:37,000 --> 01:16:41,100
In 1959, the state senate
finally clued in to the fact...

957
01:16:41,340 --> 01:16:44,470
... they couldn't buy him off
with just a $ 200 check.

958
01:16:44,680 --> 01:16:48,980
Appropriations Committee
voted an annual payment of $500...

959
01:16:49,180 --> 01:16:51,080
... just to shut him up.

960
01:16:51,280 --> 01:16:54,280
And you'd be amazed how far
Andy could stretch it.

961
01:16:54,490 --> 01:16:57,420
He made deals with book clubs,
charity groups.

962
01:16:57,620 --> 01:17:00,390
He bought remaindered books
by the pound...

963
01:17:00,890 --> 01:17:02,420
Treasure Island.

964
01:17:02,960 --> 01:17:04,290
Robert Louis...

965
01:17:04,500 --> 01:17:05,520
Stevenson.

966
01:17:05,730 --> 01:17:07,100
Fiction, adventure.

967
01:17:09,670 --> 01:17:10,690
What's next?

968
01:17:10,900 --> 01:17:13,960
I got here Auto Repair...

969
01:17:14,710 --> 01:17:15,870
...and Soap Carving.

970
01:17:16,080 --> 01:17:19,310
Trade skills and hobbies.
Under "Educational," behind you.

971
01:17:19,510 --> 01:17:21,380
Count of Monte Crisco.

972
01:17:21,850 --> 01:17:24,150
That's "Cristo," you dumb shit.

973
01:17:25,250 --> 01:17:26,240
By Alexandree...

974
01:17:26,720 --> 01:17:27,980
...Dum-ass.

975
01:17:28,320 --> 01:17:29,350
Dumb ass.

976
01:17:31,660 --> 01:17:32,720
Dumb ass?

977
01:17:35,630 --> 01:17:37,600
Dumas. IKnow what that's about?

978
01:17:39,870 --> 01:17:41,830
You'd like it.
It's about a prison break.

979
01:17:42,040 --> 01:17:45,940
We ought to file that
under "Educational" too, oughtn't we?

980
01:17:46,810 --> 01:17:50,900
The rest of us did our best
to pitch in when and where we could.

981
01:17:51,480 --> 01:17:53,240
By the year Kennedy was shot...

982
01:17:53,480 --> 01:17:57,970
... Andy had transformed a storage room
smelling of turpentine...

983
01:17:58,280 --> 01:18:01,380
... into the best prison library
in New England...

984
01:18:02,090 --> 01:18:05,020
... complete with a fine selection
of Hank Williams.

985
01:18:12,400 --> 01:18:14,330
That was also when Warden Norton...

986
01:18:14,530 --> 01:18:17,470
... instituted his famous
"Inside Out" program.

987
01:18:17,940 --> 01:18:20,000
You may remember reading about it.

988
01:18:20,240 --> 01:18:23,330
It made the papers
and got his picture in Look magazine.

989
01:18:23,540 --> 01:18:24,840
It's no free ride...

990
01:18:25,050 --> 01:18:28,280
...but rather a genuine
progressive advance...

991
01:18:28,480 --> 01:18:30,970
...in corrections and rehabilitation.

992
01:18:31,320 --> 01:18:33,840
Our inmates, properly supervised...

993
01:18:34,050 --> 01:18:36,680
...will be put to work
outside these walls...

994
01:18:36,890 --> 01:18:40,450
...performing all manner
of public service.

995
01:18:40,730 --> 01:18:42,960
These men can learn the value...

996
01:18:43,160 --> 01:18:46,960
...of an honest day's labor and
provide a service to the community...

997
01:18:47,170 --> 01:18:51,870
...at a bare minimum of expense
to Mr. And Mrs. John Q. Taxpayer.

998
01:18:52,310 --> 01:18:54,640
Of course he didn't tell the press...

999
01:18:54,840 --> 01:18:58,300
... that "bare minimum of expense"
is a fairly loose term.

1000
01:18:58,510 --> 01:19:01,540
There are 100 different ways
to skim off the top.

1001
01:19:01,750 --> 01:19:04,240
Men, materials, you name it.

1002
01:19:04,580 --> 01:19:07,490
And oh, my Lord,
how the money rolled in!

1003
01:19:07,690 --> 01:19:10,210
At this rate,
you'll put me out of business.

1004
01:19:10,420 --> 01:19:14,860
With this pool of slave labor,
you can underbid any contractor in town.

1005
01:19:15,430 --> 01:19:18,400
We're providing
a valuable community service.

1006
01:19:18,600 --> 01:19:22,260
That's fine for the papers,
but I've got a family to feed.

1007
01:19:24,940 --> 01:19:26,460
We go back a long way.

1008
01:19:27,770 --> 01:19:32,710
I need this highway contract. I don't
get it and I go under. That's a fact.

1009
01:19:33,610 --> 01:19:35,410
You have some of this fine pie...

1010
01:19:35,650 --> 01:19:38,980
...my missus made for you.
You think about that.

1011
01:19:47,260 --> 01:19:49,960
I wouldn't worry too much
about this contract.

1012
01:19:50,200 --> 01:19:53,260
I already got my boys
committed elsewhere.

1013
01:19:55,240 --> 01:19:58,300
You be sure and thank Maisie
for this fine pie.

1014
01:19:59,410 --> 01:20:01,570
And behind every shady deal...

1015
01:20:01,910 --> 01:20:04,540
... behind every dollar earned...

1016
01:20:04,810 --> 01:20:07,870
... there was Andy, keeping the books.

1017
01:20:08,280 --> 01:20:09,540
Two deposits.

1018
01:20:09,780 --> 01:20:13,910
Maine National and New England First.
Night drops as always, sir.

1019
01:20:44,120 --> 01:20:48,450
Get my stuff to the laundry. Two suits
for dry-clean and a bag of whatnot.

1020
01:20:48,920 --> 01:20:52,450
If they over-starch my shirts again,
they'll hear from me.

1021
01:20:52,660 --> 01:20:53,990
How do I look?

1022
01:20:55,030 --> 01:20:57,520
- Very nice.
