1270
01:35:21,430 --> 01:35:24,230
The kid passed. C + average.

1271
01:35:24,430 --> 01:35:26,520
Thought you'd like to know.

1272
01:35:42,750 --> 01:35:44,220
Warden wants to talk.

1273
01:35:57,960 --> 01:35:59,020
Out here?

1274
01:35:59,230 --> 01:36:01,460
That's what the man said.

1275
01:36:17,580 --> 01:36:18,570
Warden?

1276
01:36:28,590 --> 01:36:32,660
I'm asking you to keep this conversation
just between us.

1277
01:36:34,170 --> 01:36:36,430
I feel awkward enough as it is.

1278
01:36:54,890 --> 01:36:56,950
We got a situation here.

1279
01:36:57,820 --> 01:36:59,920
I think you can appreciate that.

1280
01:37:00,130 --> 01:37:01,350
Yes, sir.

1281
01:37:01,630 --> 01:37:03,030
I sure can.

1282
01:37:03,300 --> 01:37:07,320
I tell you, son, this thing really
came along and knocked my wind out.

1283
01:37:08,800 --> 01:37:11,360
It's got me up nights.
That's the truth.

1284
01:37:13,640 --> 01:37:15,470
The right thing to do...

1285
01:37:17,140 --> 01:37:20,870
...sometimes it's hard to know
what that is.

1286
01:37:21,880 --> 01:37:23,310
Do you understand?

1287
01:37:25,620 --> 01:37:27,210
I need your help, son.

1288
01:37:28,650 --> 01:37:30,820
If I'm going to move on this...

1289
01:37:31,160 --> 01:37:34,320
...there can't be
the least little shred of doubt.

1290
01:37:35,060 --> 01:37:36,120
I have to know...

1291
01:37:36,330 --> 01:37:38,960
...if what you told Dufresne
was the truth.

1292
01:37:39,160 --> 01:37:40,290
Yes, sir.

1293
01:37:40,500 --> 01:37:41,730
Absolutely.

1294
01:37:42,230 --> 01:37:45,230
Would you be willing to swear
before a judge and jury...

1295
01:37:45,440 --> 01:37:47,430
...with your hand on the Good Book...

1296
01:37:47,640 --> 01:37:50,300
...and take an oath
before Almighty God himself?

1297
01:37:50,510 --> 01:37:52,310
Just give me that chance.

1298
01:37:56,580 --> 01:37:57,910
That's what I thought.

1299
01:38:45,000 --> 01:38:46,900
I'm sure by now you've heard.

1300
01:38:48,670 --> 01:38:49,690
Terrible thing.

1301
01:38:51,300 --> 01:38:52,770
A man that young...

1302
01:38:53,110 --> 01:38:55,700
...less than a year to go,
trying to escape.

1303
01:38:56,240 --> 01:38:58,730
Broke Captain Hadley's heart
to shoot him.

1304
01:38:59,480 --> 01:39:00,970
Truly, it did.

1305
01:39:03,980 --> 01:39:06,420
We just have to put it behind us.

1306
01:39:08,090 --> 01:39:09,310
Move on.

1307
01:39:10,920 --> 01:39:12,410
I'm done.

1308
01:39:13,730 --> 01:39:15,350
Everything stops.

1309
01:39:17,330 --> 01:39:19,660
Get someone else to run your scams.

1310
01:39:20,930 --> 01:39:22,760
Nothing stops.

1311
01:39:24,100 --> 01:39:25,260
Nothing.

1312
01:39:28,670 --> 01:39:31,770
Or you will do
the hardest time there is.

1313
01:39:32,180 --> 01:39:34,480
No more protection from the guards.

1314
01:39:34,710 --> 01:39:39,620
I'll pull you out of that 1 -bunk Hilton
and cast you down with the sodomites.

1315
01:39:41,020 --> 01:39:43,450
You'll think you've been
fucked by a train.

1316
01:39:44,860 --> 01:39:46,350
And the library?

1317
01:39:47,030 --> 01:39:48,010
Gone.

1318
01:39:48,630 --> 01:39:51,190
Sealed off, brick by brick.

1319
01:39:51,660 --> 01:39:54,330
We'll have us a little
book barbecue in the yard.

1320
01:39:54,530 --> 01:39:56,660
They'll see the flames for miles.

1321
01:39:56,870 --> 01:39:59,700
We'll dance around it like wild Injuns.

1322
01:40:00,970 --> 01:40:03,970
You understand me? Catching my drift?

1323
01:40:07,710 --> 01:40:09,580
Or am I being obtuse?

1324
01:40:21,360 --> 01:40:23,990
Give him another month
to think about it.

1325
01:41:10,740 --> 01:41:13,800
My wife used to say
I'm a hard man to know.

1326
01:41:14,610 --> 01:41:16,440
Like a closed book.

1327
01:41:17,250 --> 01:41:19,270
Complained about it all the time.

1328
01:41:20,220 --> 01:41:21,780
She was beautiful.

1329
01:41:24,190 --> 01:41:25,710
God, I loved her.

1330
01:41:29,430 --> 01:41:31,660
I didn't know how
to show it, that's all.

1331
01:41:34,400 --> 01:41:36,060
I killed her, Red.

1332
01:41:37,940 --> 01:41:39,730
I didn't pull the trigger...

1333
01:41:41,170 --> 01:41:42,900
...but I drove her away.

1334
01:41:44,410 --> 01:41:47,110
That's why she died, because of me...

1335
01:41:47,310 --> 01:41:48,680
...the way I am.

1336
01:41:57,690 --> 01:41:59,520
That don't make you a murderer.

1337
01:42:02,890 --> 01:42:04,660
Bad husband, maybe.

1338
01:42:08,300 --> 01:42:11,570
Feel bad about it if you want,
but you didn't pull the trigger.

1339
01:42:11,770 --> 01:42:13,100
No, I didn't.

1340
01:42:13,510 --> 01:42:15,440
Somebody else did.

1341
01:42:16,680 --> 01:42:18,770
And I wound up in here.

1342
01:42:21,250 --> 01:42:22,840
Bad luck, I guess.

1343
01:42:28,050 --> 01:42:29,490
It floats around.

1344
01:42:30,520 --> 01:42:32,750
It's got to land on somebody.

1345
01:42:33,660 --> 01:42:35,560
It was my turn, that's all.

1346
01:42:36,260 --> 01:42:39,030
I was in the path of the tornado.

1347
01:42:44,970 --> 01:42:48,930
I just didn't expect the storm
would last as long as it has.

1348
01:42:53,280 --> 01:42:54,970
Think you'll ever get out of here?

1349
01:42:56,210 --> 01:42:57,240
Me?

1350
01:43:00,220 --> 01:43:01,210
Yeah.

1351
01:43:02,550 --> 01:43:04,850
One day, when I got
a long, white beard...

1352
01:43:05,060 --> 01:43:08,220
...and two or three marbles
rolling around upstairs.

1353
01:43:10,260 --> 01:43:11,890
I tell you where I'd go.

1354
01:43:13,370 --> 01:43:15,030
Zihuatanejo.

1355
01:43:15,900 --> 01:43:17,100
Say what?

1356
01:43:17,400 --> 01:43:19,230
Zihuatanejo.

1357
01:43:20,170 --> 01:43:21,830
It's in Mexico.

1358
01:43:23,210 --> 01:43:25,340
A little place on the Pacific Ocean.

1359
01:43:26,480 --> 01:43:29,280
You know what the Mexicans say
about the Pacific?

1360
01:43:31,080 --> 01:43:33,070
They say it has no memory.

1361
01:43:35,050 --> 01:43:37,720
That's where I want to live
the rest of my life.

1362
01:43:39,360 --> 01:43:41,850
A warm place with no memory.

1363
01:43:45,100 --> 01:43:47,030
Open up a little hotel...

1364
01:43:48,730 --> 01:43:50,220
...right on the beach.

1365
01:43:50,840 --> 01:43:53,030
Buy some worthless old boat...

1366
01:43:53,570 --> 01:43:55,200
...and fix it up new.

1367
01:43:57,940 --> 01:43:59,170
Take my guests out...

1368
01:44:00,010 --> 01:44:01,380
...charter fishing.

1369
01:44:05,220 --> 01:44:06,950
Zihuatanejo.

1370
01:44:10,490 --> 01:44:14,360
In a place like that, I could use
a man that knows how to get things.

1371
01:44:20,900 --> 01:44:23,730
I don't think I could make it
on the outside.

1372
01:44:30,410 --> 01:44:32,470
I been in here most of my life.

1373
01:44:33,910 --> 01:44:35,680
I'm an institutional man now.

1374
01:44:36,580 --> 01:44:38,310
Just like Brooks was.

1375
01:44:39,780 --> 01:44:41,480
You underestimate yourself.

1376
01:44:42,050 --> 01:44:43,650
I don't think so.

1377
01:44:47,490 --> 01:44:51,430
In here I'm the guy who can get things
for you, sure, but...

1378
01:44:52,200 --> 01:44:54,720
...outside all you need
is the Yellow Pages.

1379
01:44:54,930 --> 01:44:57,160
Hell, I wouldn't know
where to begin.

1380
01:44:59,300 --> 01:45:00,930
Pacific Ocean?

1381
01:45:01,340 --> 01:45:02,570
Shit.

1382
01:45:02,940 --> 01:45:05,140
Scare me to death,
something that big.

1383
01:45:05,340 --> 01:45:06,640
Not me.

1384
01:45:07,850 --> 01:45:10,610
I didn't shoot my wife,
and I didn't shoot her lover.

1385
01:45:12,350 --> 01:45:15,580
Whatever mistakes I made,
I've paid for them and then some.

1386
01:45:16,620 --> 01:45:18,110
That hotel, that boat...

1387
01:45:19,890 --> 01:45:22,120
I don't think that's too much to ask.

1388
01:45:27,030 --> 01:45:29,470
You shouldn't be doing this to yourself.

1389
01:45:29,670 --> 01:45:31,690
This is just shitty pipe dreams.

1390
01:45:32,140 --> 01:45:34,610
Mexico is way down there
and you're in here...

1391
01:45:34,810 --> 01:45:36,360
...and that's the way it is.

1392
01:45:36,710 --> 01:45:39,540
Yeah, right.
That's the way it is.

1393
01:45:41,050 --> 01:45:43,450
It's down there and I'm in here.

1394
01:45:46,020 --> 01:45:48,750
I guess it comes down
to a simple choice.

1395
01:45:51,660 --> 01:45:53,150
Get busy living...

1396
01:45:54,530 --> 01:45:56,550
...or get busy dying.

1397
01:46:08,670 --> 01:46:11,400
If you ever get out of here,
do me a favor.

1398
01:46:11,610 --> 01:46:13,870
Sure, Andy. Anything.

1399
01:46:15,750 --> 01:46:19,620
There's a big hayfield up near Buxton.
You know where Buxton is?

1400
01:46:21,090 --> 01:46:24,210
- A lot of hayfields up there.
- One in particular.

1401
01:46:24,420 --> 01:46:28,360
It's got a long rock wall
with a big oak tree at the north end.

1402
01:46:28,560 --> 01:46:31,430
It's like something
out of a Robert Frost poem.

1403
01:46:32,360 --> 01:46:34,860
It's where I asked my wife to marry me.

1404
01:46:36,270 --> 01:46:38,360
We went there for a picnic...

1405
01:46:38,770 --> 01:46:40,860
...and made love under that oak...

1406
01:46:41,540 --> 01:46:43,770
...and I asked and she said yes.

1407
01:46:47,780 --> 01:46:49,610
Promise me, Red.

1408
01:46:50,450 --> 01:46:52,080
If you ever get out...

1409
01:46:52,280 --> 01:46:53,770
...find that spot.

1410
01:46:54,950 --> 01:46:59,790
At the base of that wall, there's a rock
that has no earthly business in Maine.

1411
01:47:00,930 --> 01:47:03,950
Piece of black, volcanic glass.

1412
01:47:06,630 --> 01:47:09,290
Something's buried under it
I want you to have.

1413
01:47:10,070 --> 01:47:11,300
What, Andy?

1414
01:47:11,740 --> 01:47:13,470
What's buried under there?

1415
01:47:15,070 --> 01:47:16,940
You'll have to pry it up...

1416
01:47:17,140 --> 01:47:18,400
...to see.

1417
01:47:24,280 --> 01:47:26,250
No, I'm telling you. The guy is...

1418
01:47:26,920 --> 01:47:28,650
He's talking funny.

1419
01:47:29,750 --> 01:47:31,450
I'm really worried about him.

1420
01:47:31,860 --> 01:47:33,290
Let's keep an eye on him.

1421
01:47:33,490 --> 01:47:36,760
That's fine during the day,
but at night he's all alone.

1422
01:47:38,200 --> 01:47:39,320
Oh, Lord.

1423
01:47:40,670 --> 01:47:41,500
What?

1424
01:47:43,000 --> 01:47:45,770
Andy come down
to the loading dock today.

1425
01:47:45,970 --> 01:47:48,060
He asked me for a length of rope.

1426
01:47:48,270 --> 01:47:49,100
Rope?

1427
01:47:49,310 --> 01:47:50,970
Six feet long.

1428
01:47:51,210 --> 01:47:52,570
And you gave it to him.

1429
01:47:53,450 --> 01:47:55,240
Sure. Why wouldn't I?

1430
01:47:55,450 --> 01:47:57,010
Jesus! Heywood.

1431
01:47:57,620 --> 01:47:59,580
How was I supposed to know?

1432
01:47:59,780 --> 01:48:01,340
Remember Brooks Hatlen?

1433
01:48:03,350 --> 01:48:05,290
Andy would never do that.

1434
01:48:05,890 --> 01:48:06,950
Never.

1435
01:48:09,030 --> 01:48:10,360
I don't know.

1436
01:48:13,200 --> 01:48:15,220
Every man has his breaking point.

1437
01:48:17,570 --> 01:48:19,830
Lickety-split.
Want to get home.

1438
01:48:20,140 --> 01:48:21,900
Just about finished, sir.

1439
01:48:39,020 --> 01:48:40,650
Three deposits tonight.

1440
01:48:48,630 --> 01:48:50,530
Get my stuff down to the laundry.

1441
01:48:50,740 --> 01:48:52,360
And shine my shoes.

1442
01:48:52,570 --> 01:48:55,510
- I want them looking like mirrors.
- Yes, sir.

1443
01:49:01,010 --> 01:49:02,480
It's good having you back.

1444
01:49:03,410 --> 01:49:05,280
Place wasn't the same without you.

1445
01:49:52,160 --> 01:49:53,220
Lights out!

1446
01:50:26,060 --> 01:50:28,590
I've had some long nights in stir.

1447
01:50:29,130 --> 01:50:31,800
Alone in the dark
with nothing but your thoughts...

1448
01:50:32,000 --> 01:50:34,670
... time can draw out like a blade.

1449
01:50:40,010 --> 01:50:43,000
That was the longest night of my life.

1450
01:50:58,860 --> 01:51:00,020
Give me a count!

1451
01:51:04,540 --> 01:51:07,370
Tier 3 south, clear!

1452
01:51:10,510 --> 01:51:13,670
Man missing on tier 2, cell 245!

1453
01:51:13,880 --> 01:51:14,940
Dufresne!

1454
01:51:15,480 --> 01:51:17,910
Come out. You're holding up the show!

1455
01:51:21,050 --> 01:51:24,450
Don't make me come down
or I'll thump your skull for you!

1456
01:51:32,030 --> 01:51:35,860
Damn it, you're putting me behind!
I got a schedule to keep.

1457
01:51:36,070 --> 01:51:39,370
You'd better be sick or dead in there.
I shit you not!

1458
01:51:39,570 --> 01:51:40,900
You hear me?

1459
01:51:47,010 --> 01:51:49,100
Oh, my Holy God.

1460
01:52:06,100 --> 01:52:08,660
I want every man
on this cellblock questioned.

1461
01:52:09,100 --> 01:52:11,660
- Start with that friend of his.
- Who?

1462
01:52:14,240 --> 01:52:15,800
Open 237.

1463
01:52:19,310 --> 01:52:22,970
What do you mean, "He just wasn't here"?
Don't say that to me.

1464
01:52:23,850 --> 01:52:25,180
Don't tell me that again.

1465
01:52:25,380 --> 01:52:26,410
But sir, he wasn't.

1466
01:52:26,650 --> 01:52:30,110
I can see that, Haig!
Think I'm blind?

1467
01:52:30,790 --> 01:52:32,190
Is that what you're saying?

1468
01:52:32,390 --> 01:52:35,050
- Am I blind, Haig?
- No, sir!

1469
01:52:35,960 --> 01:52:38,450
What about you. You blind?

1470
01:52:38,960 --> 01:52:41,520
- Tell me what this is.
- Last night's count.

1471
01:52:41,730 --> 01:52:45,030
You see Dufresne's name there?
I sure do. Right there.

1472
01:52:45,240 --> 01:52:46,570
"Dufresne."

1473
01:52:48,240 --> 01:52:49,710
He was in his cell...

1474
01:52:49,940 --> 01:52:50,910
...at lights out.

1475
01:52:51,110 --> 01:52:53,370
Reasonable he'd be here in the morning.

1476
01:52:54,410 --> 01:52:56,040
I want him found.

1477
01:52:56,250 --> 01:52:59,710
Not tomorrow, not after breakfast. Now!

1478
01:52:59,950 --> 01:53:01,150
Yes, sir.

1479
01:53:02,150 --> 01:53:04,420
Let's go. Move your butts.

1480
01:53:07,830 --> 01:53:08,810
Stand.

1481
01:53:10,260 --> 01:53:11,320
Well?

1482
01:53:14,770 --> 01:53:15,760
Well, what?

1483
01:53:15,970 --> 01:53:19,430
I see you two all the time.
You're thick as thieves, you are.

1484
01:53:20,510 --> 01:53:22,000
He must have said something.

1485
01:53:22,740 --> 01:53:24,260
No, sir, Warden.

1486
01:53:24,640 --> 01:53:25,610
Not a word.

1487
01:53:27,450 --> 01:53:30,010
Lord, it's a miracle!

1488
01:53:30,620 --> 01:53:33,180
Man vanished like a fart in the wind.

1489
01:53:33,850 --> 01:53:35,010
Nothing left...

1490
01:53:35,850 --> 01:53:38,580
...but some damn rocks
on a windowsill.

1491
01:53:38,790 --> 01:53:41,520
And that cupcake on the wall.
Let's ask her.

1492
01:53:41,730 --> 01:53:43,490
Maybe she knows.

1493
01:53:43,730 --> 01:53:46,460
What say there, fuzzy-britches?
Feel like talking?

1494
01:53:47,900 --> 01:53:49,200
Guess not.

1495
01:53:49,770 --> 01:53:51,960
Why should she be any different?

1496
01:53:53,040 --> 01:53:54,700
This is a conspiracy.

1497
01:53:55,340 --> 01:53:57,170
That's what this is.

1498
01:53:57,780 --> 01:54:01,510
One big, damn conspiracy!

1499
01:54:01,780 --> 01:54:03,770
And everyone's in on it!

1500
01:54:04,420 --> 01:54:05,580
Including her!

1501
01:54:40,620 --> 01:54:42,310
In 1966...

1502
01:54:42,520 --> 01:54:44,920
... Andy Dufresne escaped...

1503
01:54:45,120 --> 01:54:46,680
... from Shawshank Prison.

1504
01:54:48,930 --> 01:54:51,490
All they found
was a muddy set of prison clothes...

1505
01:54:52,130 --> 01:54:53,650
... a bar of soap...

1506
01:54:53,870 --> 01:54:55,420
... and an old rock hammer...

1507
01:54:55,630 --> 01:54:58,100
... damn near worn down to the nub.

1508
01:55:02,610 --> 01:55:07,370
I had thought it'd take a man 600 years
to tunnel through the wall with it.

1509
01:55:08,010 --> 01:55:10,640
Old Andy did it in less than 20.

1510
01:55:28,930 --> 01:55:31,230
Oh, Andy loved geology.

1511
01:55:32,000 --> 01:55:35,170
I imagine it appealed to his
meticulous nature.

1512
01:55:35,570 --> 01:55:37,400
An ice age here...

1513
01:55:37,840 --> 01:55:40,330
... million years
of mountain building there.

1514
01:55:41,350 --> 01:55:44,180
Geology is the study
of pressure and time.

1515
01:55:45,020 --> 01:55:47,010
That's all it takes, really.

1516
01:55:47,750 --> 01:55:48,840
Pressure...

1517
01:55:49,490 --> 01:55:50,750
... and time.

1518
01:55:52,090 --> 01:55:54,150
That and a big goddamn poster.

1519
01:55:58,200 --> 01:55:59,130
Like I said...

1520
01:55:59,630 --> 01:56:03,620
... in prison, a man will do anything
to keep his mind occupied.

1521
01:56:06,440 --> 01:56:11,240
Seems Andy's favorite hobby was toting
his wall out into the exercise yard...

1522
01:56:11,780 --> 01:56:13,710
... a handful at a time.

1523
01:56:15,010 --> 01:56:17,070
I guess after Tommy was killed...

1524
01:56:17,280 --> 01:56:20,250
... Andy decided
he'd been here long enough.

1525
01:56:20,450 --> 01:56:23,010
Lickety-split.
I want to get home.

1526
01:56:23,750 --> 01:56:25,780
I'm just about finished, sir.

1527
01:56:47,240 --> 01:56:49,180
Three deposits tonight.

1528
01:56:56,490 --> 01:56:58,790
Andy did like he was told.

1529
01:56:58,990 --> 01:57:02,480
Buffed those shoes
to a high mirror-shine.

1530
01:57:06,160 --> 01:57:08,460
The guards simply didn't notice.

1531
01:57:08,770 --> 01:57:10,230
Neither did I.

1532
01:57:10,430 --> 01:57:11,960
I mean, seriously...

1533
01:57:12,170 --> 01:57:15,160
... how often do you really look
at a man's shoes?

1534
01:59:18,730 --> 01:59:21,890
Andy crawled to freedom
through 500 yards...

1535
01:59:22,130 --> 01:59:25,470
... of shit-smelling foulness
I can't even imagine.

1536
01:59:26,470 --> 01:59:28,800
Or maybe I just don't want to.

1537
01:59:33,210 --> 01:59:35,580
Five hundred yards.

1538
01:59:36,080 --> 01:59:39,140
That's the length
of five football fields.

1539
01:59:39,780 --> 01:59:42,340
Just shy of half a mile.

1540
02:00:37,580 --> 02:00:42,170
The next morning, right about the time
Raquel was spilling her secret...

1541
02:00:42,480 --> 02:00:45,310
... a man nobody ever
laid eyes on before...

1542
02:00:45,550 --> 02:00:48,140
... strolled into
the Maine National Bank.

1543
02:00:48,720 --> 02:00:51,880
Until that moment,
he didn't exist.

1544
02:00:52,460 --> 02:00:54,820
- Except on paper.
- May I help you?

1545
02:00:55,230 --> 02:00:57,160
He had all the proper ID...

1546
02:00:57,360 --> 02:01:01,060
... driver's license, birth certificate,
Social Security card...

1547
02:01:01,500 --> 02:01:04,020
And the signature
was a spot-on match.

1548
02:01:04,240 --> 02:01:07,330
I must say I'm sorry
to be losing your business.

1549
02:01:07,540 --> 02:01:09,270
I hope you'll enjoy living abroad.

1550
02:01:10,070 --> 02:01:11,170
Thank you.

1551
02:01:11,840 --> 02:01:13,000
I'm sure I will.

1552
02:01:13,910 --> 02:01:17,240
Here's your cashier's check, sir.
Will there be anything else?

1553
02:01:17,450 --> 02:01:18,440
Please.

1554
02:01:19,020 --> 02:01:21,510
Would you add this
to your outgoing mail?

1555
02:01:22,020 --> 02:01:23,210
I'd be happy to.

1556
02:01:25,020 --> 02:01:26,350
Good day, sir.

1557
02:01:27,290 --> 02:01:31,730
Mr. Stevens visited nearly a dozen banks
in the Portland area that morning.

1558
02:01:32,200 --> 02:01:33,790
All told, he blew town...

1559
02:01:34,000 --> 02:01:38,830
... with better than $370,000
of Warden Norton's money.

1560
02:01:39,540 --> 02:01:42,300
Severance pay for 19 years.

1561
02:01:49,550 --> 02:01:51,740
Good morning, Portland Daily Bugle.

1562
02:02:44,600 --> 02:02:47,540
Byron Hadley?
You have the right to remain silent.

1563
02:02:47,810 --> 02:02:52,240
If you give up this right, anything you
say can be held against you in court.

1564
02:02:52,680 --> 02:02:57,140
I wasn't there to see, but I hear
Byron Hadley sobbed like a girl...

1565
02:02:57,350 --> 02:02:58,840
... when they took him away.

1566
02:03:04,720 --> 02:03:08,120
Norton had no intention
of going that quietly.

1567
02:03:23,970 --> 02:03:24,800
Samuel Norton.

1568
02:03:25,610 --> 02:03:28,040
We have a warrant
for your arrest. Open up.

1569
02:03:32,780 --> 02:03:33,880
Open the door.

1570
02:03:34,420 --> 02:03:35,680
I'm not sure which key.

1571
02:03:45,830 --> 02:03:47,760
Make it easy on yourself, Norton!

1572
02:03:59,280 --> 02:04:02,730
I like to think the last thing
that went through his head...

1573
02:04:02,950 --> 02:04:04,540
... other than that bullet...

1574
02:04:04,750 --> 02:04:09,190
... was to wonder how the hell
Andy Dufresne ever got the best of him.

1575
02:04:11,690 --> 02:04:15,150
Not long after the warden
deprived us of his company...

1576
02:04:15,430 --> 02:04:17,490
... I got a postcard in the mail.

1577
02:04:18,960 --> 02:04:21,800
It was blank,
but the postmark said...

1578
02:04:22,000 --> 02:04:24,130
... Fort Hancock, Texas.

1579
02:04:24,670 --> 02:04:26,030
Fort Hancock...

1580
02:04:26,300 --> 02:04:28,030
... right on the border.

1581
02:04:28,440 --> 02:04:30,430
That's where Andy crossed.

1582
02:04:31,010 --> 02:04:35,140
When I picture him heading south
in his own car with the top down...

1583
02:04:35,480 --> 02:04:37,710
... it always makes me laugh.

1584
02:04:39,550 --> 02:04:41,110
Andy Dufresne...

1585
02:04:41,490 --> 02:04:43,510
... who crawled through
a river of shit...

1586
02:04:43,720 --> 02:04:46,120
... and came out clean
on the other side.

1587
02:04:46,960 --> 02:04:48,320
Andy Dufresne...

1588
02:04:49,130 --> 02:04:50,720
... headed for the Pacific.

1589
02:04:53,700 --> 02:04:55,860
Hadley's got him
by the throat, right?

1590
02:04:56,070 --> 02:04:59,870
He says, " I believe this boy's
about to have himself an accident."

1591
02:05:00,070 --> 02:05:02,940
Those of us who knew him best
talk about him often.

1592
02:05:03,610 --> 02:05:05,300
I swear, the stuff he pulled...

1593
02:05:05,510 --> 02:05:08,480
"My friends could use
a couple of beers."

1594
02:05:08,810 --> 02:05:10,470
And he got it!

1595
02:05:11,720 --> 02:05:14,120
Sometimes it makes me sad, though...

1596
02:05:14,380 --> 02:05:15,820
... Andy being gone.

1597
02:05:16,520 --> 02:05:20,650
I have to remind myself that
some birds aren't meant to be caged.

1598
02:05:21,120 --> 02:05:23,180
Their feathers are just too bright.

1599
02:05:24,900 --> 02:05:26,620
And when they fly away...

1600
02:05:27,060 --> 02:05:31,470
... the part of you that knows it was
a sin to lock them up does rejoice.

1601
02:05:32,540 --> 02:05:33,800
But still...

1602
02:05:34,270 --> 02:05:38,610
... the place you live in is that much
more drab and empty that they're gone.

1603
02:05:42,810 --> 02:05:45,180
I guess I just miss my friend.

1604
02:06:09,870 --> 02:06:10,810
Please sit down.

1605
02:06:16,650 --> 02:06:18,210
Ellis Boyd Redding...

1606
02:06:18,750 --> 02:06:22,010
...your files say you've served
40 years of a life sentence.

1607
02:06:22,820 --> 02:06:24,950
You feel you've been rehabilitated?

1608
02:06:26,820 --> 02:06:28,380
Rehabilitated?

1609
02:06:30,430 --> 02:06:32,330
Well, now, let me see.

1610
02:06:33,330 --> 02:06:35,660
I don't have any idea
what that means.

1611
02:06:37,770 --> 02:06:40,030
It means you're ready
to rejoin society...

1612
02:06:40,600 --> 02:06:42,940
I know what you think it means, sonny.

1613
02:06:45,110 --> 02:06:47,100
To me it's just a made-up word.

1614
02:06:48,450 --> 02:06:50,780
A politician's word so that...

1615
02:06:51,210 --> 02:06:54,740
...young fellas like yourself
can wear a suit and a tie...

1616
02:06:55,220 --> 02:06:56,810
...and have a job.

1617
02:06:58,790 --> 02:07:00,880
What do you really want to know?

1618
02:07:01,660 --> 02:07:03,630
Am I sorry for what I did?

1619
02:07:04,060 --> 02:07:05,220
Well, are you?

1620
02:07:07,130 --> 02:07:09,960
There's not a day goes by
I don't feel regret.

1621
02:07:11,340 --> 02:07:14,790
Not because I'm in here
or because you think I should.

1622
02:07:18,280 --> 02:07:20,840
I look back on the way I was then...

1623
02:07:22,980 --> 02:07:24,140
...a young...

1624
02:07:25,250 --> 02:07:28,740
...stupid kid who committed
that terrible crime.

1625
02:07:31,760 --> 02:07:33,450
I want to talk to him.

1626
02:07:35,390 --> 02:07:37,860
I want to try
and talk some sense to him.

1627
02:07:38,600 --> 02:07:40,530
Tell him the way things are.

1628
02:07:42,630 --> 02:07:44,070
But I can't.

1629
02:07:46,270 --> 02:07:48,260
That kid's long gone...

1630
02:07:49,470 --> 02:07:52,240
...and this old man is all that's left.

1631
02:07:53,640 --> 02:07:55,110
I got to live with that.

1632
02:07:56,480 --> 02:07:58,180
Rehabilitated?

1633
02:07:58,550 --> 02:08:00,380
It's just a bullshit word.

1634
02:08:01,320 --> 02:08:06,090
So you go on and stamp your forms,
sonny, and stop wasting my time.

1635
02:08:07,320 --> 02:08:09,590
Because to tell you the truth...

1636
02:08:09,930 --> 02:08:11,920
...I don't give a shit.

1637
02:09:38,450 --> 02:09:39,850
Here you go, miss.

1638
02:09:42,790 --> 02:09:43,810
Restroom break?

1639
02:09:49,630 --> 02:09:54,150
You don't need to ask me every time
you need to go take a piss. Just go.

1640
02:10:07,210 --> 02:10:10,270
Forty years I've been asking
permission to piss.

1641
02:10:11,110 --> 02:10:14,110
I can't squeeze a drop without say-so.

1642
02:10:17,620 --> 02:10:19,780
There's a harsh truth to face.

1643
02:10:21,460 --> 02:10:24,360
No way I'm going to make it
on the outside.

1644
02:10:32,240 --> 02:10:35,930
All I do anymore is think of ways
to break my parole...

1645
02:10:36,740 --> 02:10:39,210
... so maybe they'd send me back.

1646
02:10:44,410 --> 02:10:46,850
Terrible thing, to live in fear.

1647
02:10:47,750 --> 02:10:49,410
Brooks Hatlen knew it.

1648
02:10:49,620 --> 02:10:51,550
Knew it all too well.

1649
02:10:53,160 --> 02:10:56,560
All I want is to be back
where things make sense.

1650
02:10:56,990 --> 02:10:59,720
Where I won't have to be afraid
all the time.

1651
02:11:01,730 --> 02:11:04,100
Only one thing stops me.

1652
02:11:05,540 --> 02:11:07,940
A promise I made to Andy.

1653
02:11:28,460 --> 02:11:29,580
There it is.

1654
02:11:40,200 --> 02:11:41,860
Much obliged, sir.

1655
02:15:21,190 --> 02:15:22,450
Dear Red:

1656
02:15:22,690 --> 02:15:25,160
If you're reading this,
you've gotten out...

1657
02:15:25,360 --> 02:15:29,420
... and if you've come this far,
maybe you'd come a bit further.

1658
02:15:29,700 --> 02:15:32,170
You remember the name
of the town, don't you?

1659
02:15:34,470 --> 02:15:35,960
Zihuatanejo.

1660
02:15:37,610 --> 02:15:41,200
I could use a good man
to help me get my project on wheels.

1661
02:15:41,710 --> 02:15:45,240
I'll keep an eye out for you,
and the chessboard ready.

1662
02:15:46,050 --> 02:15:47,450
Remember, Red...

1663
02:15:47,780 --> 02:15:49,880
... hope is a good thing...

1664
02:15:50,090 --> 02:15:52,080
... maybe the best of things.

1665
02:15:52,290 --> 02:15:54,450
And no good thing ever dies.

1666
02:15:54,990 --> 02:15:57,860
I will be hoping
that this letter finds you...

1667
02:15:58,060 --> 02:15:59,790
... and finds you well.

1668
02:16:00,300 --> 02:16:01,520
Your friend...

1669
02:16:01,730 --> 02:16:02,890
... Andy.

1670
02:16:36,730 --> 02:16:38,460
"Get busy living...

1671
02:16:38,670 --> 02:16:40,570
... or get busy dying. "

1672
02:16:43,270 --> 02:16:45,430
That's goddamn right.

1673
02:16:50,680 --> 02:16:52,810
For the second time in my life...

1674
02:16:53,050 --> 02:16:55,610
... I'm guilty of committing a crime.

1675
02:16:56,690 --> 02:16:58,620
Parole violation.

1676
02:16:59,290 --> 02:17:02,950
Of course I doubt they'll toss up
any roadblocks for that.

1677
02:17:03,630 --> 02:17:05,650
Not for an old crook like me.

1678
02:17:05,860 --> 02:17:07,890
Fort Hancock, Texas, please.

1679
02:17:11,570 --> 02:17:16,300
I find I'm so excited I can barely
sit still or hold a thought in my head.

1680
02:17:16,740 --> 02:17:20,070
I think it's the excitement
only a free man can feel.

1681
02:17:20,280 --> 02:17:22,770
A free man at the start
of a long journey...

1682
02:17:22,980 --> 02:17:25,570
... whose conclusion is uncertain.

1683
02:17:28,590 --> 02:17:31,250
I hope I can make it across the border.

1684
02:17:32,760 --> 02:17:35,780
I hope to see my friend
and shake his hand.

1685
02:17:37,660 --> 02:17:41,720
I hope the Pacific is as blue
as it has been in my dreams.

1686
02:17:43,570 --> 02:17:44,760
I hope.

